replyContent: Please write to us again at info@borenson.com so that we can address both concerns. Also, indicate the two problems which "cannot be solved".  Thank you.

content: Fun way to learn Algebra to prep me for the GED. My only gripes are 1: There's no "help" if you're stuck on a particular exercise, other than taking you back to the video which only explains only one scenario. At least a written explanation of how to solve each individual exercise should be provided as a minimum, as you can't progress to the next exercise without solving the previous one. 2: The video is small, only using a small portion of my Samsung S9's screen, making it difficult to view.
Excellent. I concur with other comments, I too would continue to purchase these tutorials if more and more are made. It is Brilliant.
absolutely amazing he makes it understandable

I love these! Own all 3! My only recommendation would be, make expansion packs for each series that we can purchase additionally. No videos, or tutorials, but more problems to solve, for those of us who'd like to keep the information fresh and practice with more available problems! Provide expansion packs with 100 problems or so from each series, 1, 2, and 3 individually, that we can purchase additionally! 5 bucks or so for each of the series relative expansion packs, with additional problems for us to work out and have fun with, would be 15 dollars more for each potential user to purchase. Either way, I love these apps! Thanks for an incredible way to make the Algebra I missed in school, so incredibly easy to understand! Highly recommended to any and all who want to understand the hidden simplicity of Algebra, that seemed like a confusing mystery to so many of us before :)

This method of using pawns and number cubes is how I learned algebra in my grade school gifted program and it's something that I like to use today when tutoring students who are uncomfortable with basic algebra. I wouldn't mind also seeing an app that is just the board, number cubes and pawns on their own (outside of the context of specific progressing lessons) so students can model their homework problems.
